Step 1 â€“ Start with the User
â€œA user accesses a region-specific domain like us.smartenspaces.com.â€
Step 2 â€“ DNS
â€œDNS resolves this domain to a region-specific public IP.â€
Step 3 â€“ Azure Load Balancer
â€œThat IP belongs to an Azure Load Balancer created for the Ingress Controller.â€
Step 4 â€“ Ingress Controller
â€œTraffic enters Kubernetes through an NGINX Ingress Controller installed via Helm. TLS is terminated here.â€
Step 5 â€“ Routing
â€œIngress uses host- and path-based routing to forward traffic.â€
Step 6 â€“ Internal Services
â€œRequests are routed to internal ClusterIP services, which forward traffic to pods.â€
Step 7 â€“ Pods
â€œEach pod runs a microservice like EMS, TMS, or Space Management.â€
Final Line (Very Important)
â€œOnly the Ingress is exposed externally; all services remain internal.â€
4ï¸âƒ£ â€œWHY THIS DESIGN?â€ (ARCHITECT JUSTIFICATION)
âœ… Why separate public IPs per environment?
Fault isolation (US outage â‰  India outage)
Independent scaling
Easier compliance & audits
Clear ownership per region
âœ… Why Ingress + ClusterIP?
Strong security (no public services)
Centralized TLS & routing
Kubernetes best practice
âœ… Why Helm for Ingress?
Version-controlled deployments
Easy upgrades & rollback
Consistent environment setup
âœ… Why namespaces?
Logical environment isolation
RBAC and access control
Resource quotas per environment
âœ… Why TLS at Ingress?
Simplified certificate management
Reduced application complexity
Standardized HTTPS enforcement
5ï¸âƒ£ ONE-PAGE EXECUTIVE SUMMARY (MEMORIZE THIS)
â€œWe implemented a multi-region Kubernetes architecture on Azure where each environment has its own public entry point and Ingress layer. Traffic is securely terminated and routed at the Ingress, while backend services remain internal and isolated using namespaces. This design ensures scalability, security, fault isolation, and operational consistency across environments.â€
